Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Innes,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: shortened form of   McInnis  , from Gaelic <b>Mag Aonghuis</b> ‘son of Aonghus’.","Scottish: habitational name from the barony of Innes in Urquhart (Morayshire), named from Gaelic <i>inis</i> ‘island’.","English: variant of   Ince  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Inniss","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Innes  ."]},{"name":"Ince","meanings":["habitational name from Ince in Makerfield (Lancashire), Ince (Cheshire), or Ince Blundell (Lancashire). The placenames derive from Proto-Welsh <i>ïnïs</i> ‘island’.","possibly a post-medieval West Midlands variant of <b>Hints</b>, a habitational name from either of two places called Hints (Staffordshire, Shropshire). The placenames probably derive from Proto-Welsh <i>hïnt</i> ‘way, path’ + Middle English plural <i>-es</i>.","possibly a variant with plural or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i> of <i>Inn</i>, from residence at an <i>inn</i> or <i>inns</i>, from Middle English <i>in</i> (singular) or <i>innes</i> (plural) ‘tavern, lodging(s), tenement(s)’. There seems also to have been some confusion with Scottish   Innes  ."]},{"name":"Inch","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Innes  .","English: perhaps, at least in some cases, a variant of   Ince  .","English: variant of   Hinch  ."]},{"name":"McInnis","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Aonghuis</b>, a patronymic from the personal name <i>Aonghus</i> (see   Angus  ). See also   McInnes  , compare Irish   McGinnis  ."]},{"name":"Innis","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Innes  .","English: variant of   Ince  ."]},{"name":"Inness","meanings":["Scottish (Durham and Northumberland): variant of   Innes  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady William de Innes, VI married Sir William de Innes 6th of Innes - of that Ilk before 1300, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1270–1320":"1270–1320","1300–1372":"1300–1372","–Female":"Surnud","Abt 1300":"umbes 1300","before 1300":"enne 1300","1300":"1300","1320":"1320","1372":"1372","1270":"1270","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1270–1320":"1270–1320","1300–1372":"1300–1372","–Female":"Kuollut","Abt 1300":"noin 1300","before 1300":"ennen vuotta 1300","1300":"1300","1320":"1320","1372":"1372","1270":"1270","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","1270–1320":"1270–1320","1300–1372":"1300–1372","–Female":"Décédée","Abt 1300":"environ 1300","before 1300":"avant 1300","1300":"1300","1320":"1320","1372":"1372","1270":"1270","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Écosse, Royaume-Uni","Scotland":"Écosse","lifeSummary":"Lady William de Innes, VI a épousé Sir William de Innes 6th of Innes - of that Ilk avant 1300, à Écosse. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils."},"de":{"–":"Verstorben","1270–1320":